question:
Give feedback to your teammate by completing the following sentence:

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: Jason
value:
I want to work with you because you have some background knowledge in computer programming fundamentals, you think of edge cases, and problems a program may run in to and I would want to work with you more if you developed your culture and especially your TEAM PLAY skills in the following areas:
1. Belonging Tension (They were in relationship with me. They cared for the quality of our working relationship, and paid attention to it.) 
 An example of this is when you would disagree with me about preferences in writing code: eliminating semi-colons, adding a space at the end of a componentâ€™s closing bracket. You questioned my ideas 80% of the time and I often had to prove that my ideas were equally valid. I felt that I had to clear my ideas with you before they could be implemented in our code. At the end of the day, these opinions/preferences took away from our ability to work as a team and accomplish tasks together. 
I was mindful of working better with you and would sacrifice my ideas to make sure yours were heard, whenever I did so there was less friction and time spent idly arguing over opinions.
My feedback for you here is focus on getting to the right answer together and making everyone in your team feel valued and that their ideas are validated.
2. Friction Reduction (They were constantly looking for ways to improve team process, and to help everyone play to their full potential.)
An example of this is when you would disagree with me without asking more questions to fully understand my ideas. You were very focused on the â€˜rightnessâ€™ of a programming concept. You argued with me about whether a function was an expression or a declaration when I had already told you the â€˜rightâ€™ answer. You were not focused on helping to improve team process by avoiding unnecessary and emotionally draining arguments. There are many ways to do a task in Javascript so claiming that your way is the right way is not useful in a team. 
3. Flexible Leadership (They stepped into leadership roles when needed, and supported others to step into leading roles.)
An example of this is, during our first few days working together, you shut my ideas down by telling me, â€œYou are wrong.â€ Your words and communication style did not support me in stepping into leadership roles. You were quick to give criticism but not as quick at giving supporting or encouraging words.
My feedback for you here is to incorporate more inclusive language into your communication, communicate with your team mate in the way they can best grow and learn, and encourage/support them through words. 
4. Receptiveness (They were open to feedback, and received it gracefully without becoming defensive or dismissive. They separated their ego from their work.)
When I gave you feedback, I told it to you objectively while exposing my own vulnerability. You were especially defensive and dismissive about feedback on how to work with team mates who do not come from the same level of privilege and identity. 
My feedback to you here is to be more open to feedback, especially about privilege, gender, race and culture and how this plays in to team dynamics.

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: Mark Suzuki
value:
I want to work with you because you're open to new ideas. I like that you get excited with new technologies. Even when faced with incredibly challenging concepts and code, you chug right through it. At the same time, I appreciate that you expressed difficulty with it, but in a positive way. You were honest about the irritating and annoying parts about react, yet open to a multitude of options.

I would want to work with you more if you feel more confident in your leadership; your ability to take control of the situation and dictate terms. I felt like I often was accidentally leading the way or taking complete control over the direction of the project, and when asking you for your opinion I struggled to gauge your enthusiasm. I would have felt more settled if you offered reassurance upon agreeing to move away from react and back to standard node, if that indeed was what you wanted, and if it wasn't what you wanted, would appreciate being corrected. (Take with a grain of salt, this was a very particular circumstance and only added minor confusion)
